Building LDA model to model the topics in the speeches

Data Preprocessing:

countries <- c('united states', 'england', 'france', 'italy', 'germany', 'japan', 'canada', 'russia')
speeches_preprocessed <- pre_process_corpus_adam(speeches, "text", extra_stopwords = countries, root_gen = 'lemmatize')
save.image(file = "lab5_workspace.RData")
write.csv(speeches_preprocessed, file = "lab5_preprocessed_data.csv")

Building DTM and converting it to a sparse corpus:

it <- itoken(speeches_preprocessed, tokenizer = word_tokenizer)
vocab_full <- create_vocabulary(it, ngram = c(1, 3))
lbound <- 2
ubound <- 45

vocab <- vocab_full[vocab_full$doc_count > lbound & vocab_full$doc_count < ubound,]

vectorizer <- vocab_vectorizer(vocab)
dtm <- create_dtm(it, vectorizer)
dim(dtm)

sparse_corpus <- Matrix(dtm, sparse = T)

1.

Define systematic approach for optimizing K, the number of topics. You can use functions designed for this task or your own methods. Explain how your approach works and why it is effective. Optimizing K (number of topics)

# converting matrix into document-level list of vocab counts
docs <- apply(dtm, 1, function(x){
  tmp <- as.data.frame(x)
  tmp$vocab <- 1:nrow(tmp)
  tmp <- tmp[tmp[,1] >0,]
  tmp <- as.matrix.data.frame(t(tmp[, c(2,1)]))
  return(tmp)
})

# running ksearch function and analyze results
ksearch <- searchK(documents = docs, vocab = colnames(dtm), K = c(3:21))
df <- data.frame(K = c(1:19), residual = unlist(ksearch$results$residual))
ggplot(data = df, aes(y = residual, x = K)) + geom_point()

plot(ksearch)

With ksearch we can evaluate our model based on metrics like the residuals, the semantic coherence of the topics, the likelihood for held-out datasets. Above plots briefly summarizes how our models are performing at different numbers of topics (K). However these measures are not the best. They are still inferior to human validation of the topic models by carefully inspecting not only the top words associated with each document.

The residuals are low around 10- 13 (lowest at 11), so perhaps a good number of topics would be around there. Also the semantic coherence is the score plateaus after 12 topics. The semantic coherence is maximized when the most probable words in a given topic frequently co-occur together, and its a metric that correlates well with human judgment of topic quality. Having high semantic coherence is relatively easy, though, if you only have a few topics dominated by very common words, so it is better to look at both semantic coherence and exclusivity of words to topics to study the tradeoff. So the best guess for the number of topics would be around 11.

2.

Analyze how the G8 countries align on topics and how that alignment has changed over time.

topic_model2 <- stm(sparse_corpus, init.type = 'LDA', seed = 12345,
                   K = 11, control = list(alpha = 64))

topic_prevalence <- as.data.frame(topic_model2$theta)
mean(apply(topic_prevalence, 1, max))
topic_content <- as.data.frame(t(exp(topic_model2$beta$logbeta[[1]])))
topic_names <- apply(topic_content, 2, function(x) {paste(topic_model2$vocab[order(x,
                                      decreasing = T)[1:6]], collapse = " ")})
topic_names
df <- topic_prevalence
colnames(df) <- topic_names
df$year <- as.character(speeches$year)
df <- melt(df, id.vars = 'year', value.name = 'proportion', variable.name = 'topic')

ggplot(df, aes(x = topic, y = proportion, fill = topic)) + geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), axis.text.y = element_blank(), legend.position = "none") +  
  coord_flip() + facet_wrap(~ year, ncol = 9)

3.

Create at least 3 visualizations to analyze these trends. Explain your results.

Below visualizations shows that topics related to the federal government as well as inner conflicts dominates the first decades. On the other hand, topics related to economy & terrorism are the most important topics of recent addresses.

df <- topic_prevalence
colnames(df) <- topic_names
df$year <- as.character(speeches$year)
df <- melt(df, id.vars = 'year', value.name = 'proportion', variable.name = 'topic')

df$decade <- paste0(substr(df$year, 0, 3), "0")
df <- df %>% group_by(decade, topic) %>% summarize(Value = mean(proportion))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'decade' (override with `.groups` argument)
ggplot(df, aes(x = decade, y =Value, fill = topic)) + geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
  scale_fill_manual(values = paste0(alphabet(20), "FF"), name = "topic") +

Wordclouds for top topics by decade:

library(wordcloud2)
library(htmlwidgets)
library(webshot)
#webshot::install_phantomjs()

wc <- function(x, topic_model, topic_content) {

# visualize topics as word cloud
topicToViz <- x # change for your own topic of interest

top40terms <- apply(topic_content, 2, function(x) {topic_model$vocab[order(x, decreasing = T)[1:40]]})[,topicToViz]
words <- (top40terms)
# extract the probabilities of each of the 40 terms
probabilities <- sort(topic_content[,topicToViz], decreasing =T)[1:40]
# visualize the terms as wordcloud
return(wordcloud2(data.frame(words, probabilities), shuffle = FALSE, size = 0.8))}




a <- result %>%
